  "notes": "Standard German (Hochdeutsch / BГјhnendeutsch). AUSLAUTVERHГ„RTUNG: obstruents devoiced word-finally (bв†’p, dв†’t, gв†’k, vв†’f); the engine only computes WORD_FINAL position (no medial-coda syllabification), so devoicing before a following consonant inside a word, e.g. 'Abschied', is a known engine-limit exception, not a spec gap. SP/ST: [Кѓp]/[Кѓt] word-initially, [sp]/[st] elsewhere. CH (ich-Laut/ach-Laut): [x] after back vowels a/o/u (and the au/eu-initial diphthong graphemes, whose first letter is a/e), [Г§] after front vowels e/i, after consonants, and word-initially before front vowels. The GraphemePosition enum only encodes AFTER_A/E/I/O/U for single-letter vowel graphemes, so вџЁchвџ© after the umlauts Г¤/Г¶/Гј or the diphthongs eu/Г¤u falls back to the generic after_vowel bucket, which defaults to the more frequent ich-Laut [Г§] вЂ” a known engine-limit exception. Glottal stop insertion before vowel-initial syllables (Kohler 1990; Wikipedia German phonology) is attested but not phonemic and frequently absent even in careful speech outside northern varieties, and is not encoded in wikipron-style gold transcriptions used for benchmarking, so it is deliberately not inserted to avoid a spurious PER regression. Vowel length follows the orthographic single/double-consonant and Dehnungs-h/doubled-vowel/вџЁieвџ© conventions described in Wikipedia's German orthography article, consistent with Wiese (1996) and Hall (2003). Sources: Wiese (1996), Hall (2003), Mangold (2005), Wikipedia German phonology, Wikipedia German orthography.",
